Note:
RING BUFFER - SPSC Byte Ring Buffer Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements a single-producer single-consumer (SPSC) byte
ring buffer. It is the building block for streaming pipelines where
one stage produces bytes and another consumes them - lexer pump-ahead
buffers, syscall I/O buffering, log line buffering, MIDI/serial-style
byte streams, etc.

Design notes:
  - Storage holds capacity + 1 bytes so the empty-vs-full distinction
    can be made by head == tail (empty) vs head == (tail + 1) mod cap.
    This avoids carrying a separate size counter on the hot path.
  - Both head (read cursor) and tail (write cursor) advance modulo
    the allocated size (capacity + 1).
  - Wrap-around is handled by splitting reads and writes into at most
    two contiguous spans against the backing array.
  - The buffer is not thread-safe by itself; SPSC safety requires the
    producer and consumer to use proper memory-ordering primitives
    around the head/tail loads which is outside this module's scope.
    The structure layout is, however, future-compatible with such
    primitives because head and tail are aligned at 8-byte offsets.

Ring buffer structure (32 bytes):
  offset 0:  data pointer  (8 bytes)
  offset 8:  head index    (8 bytes) - next byte to read
  offset 16: tail index    (8 bytes) - next byte to write
  offset 24: alloc_size    (8 bytes) - capacity + 1 (backing array bytes)

Logical capacity reported by rb_capacity is alloc_size - 1.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let RB_HEADER_SIZE be 32
Let RB_MIN_CAPACITY be 16

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION / DESTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create a ring buffer with the requested logical byte capacity. The
internal allocation is capacity + 1 bytes to support the head/tail
empty-vs-full distinction without a separate count.

A capacity below RB_MIN_CAPACITY is rounded up to RB_MIN_CAPACITY so
small consumers never pay the cost of allocating a tiny page.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Clamp capacity to at least RB_MIN_CAPACITY.
2) Allocate the 32-byte header.
3) Allocate (capacity + 1) bytes for storage; zero it.
4) Initialize head = 0, tail = 0, alloc_size = capacity + 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity) for the storage zero-fill.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure. The zero-fill of storage prevents
information leakage between allocations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_create" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Let real_capacity be capacity
    If real_capacity is less than RB_MIN_CAPACITY:
        Set real_capacity to RB_MIN_CAPACITY
    End If
    Let rb be proc allocate from Layout with RB_HEADER_SIZE
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let alloc_size be real_capacity plus 1
    Let data be proc allocate from Layout with alloc_size
    If data is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with rb
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_fill from Memory with data, 0, alloc_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 0, data
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 24, alloc_size
    Return rb
End Process

@Reasoning
Release the ring buffer, freeing storage and header.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Frees the data pointer (if non-null) then the header.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) at the allocator boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-owned; do not double-free.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_destroy" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    If data is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with data
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with rb
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STATE QUERIES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Logical capacity of the ring buffer (alloc_size - 1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns alloc_size - 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_capacity" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Return alloc_size minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Number of bytes currently readable. Computed as (tail - head + alloc_size)
mod alloc_size, expressed as a positive value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read head and tail.
2) If tail >= head, return tail - head.
3) Otherwise return tail + alloc_size - head.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_available_read" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 16
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    If tail is greater than or equal to head:
        Return tail minus head
    End If
    Return (tail plus alloc_size) minus head
End Process

@Reasoning
Number of bytes that can be written before the buffer is full.
Equal to capacity - available_read.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Computes capacity - available_read where capacity = alloc_size - 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_available_write" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let capacity be alloc_size minus 1
    Let used be proc rb_available_read with rb
    Return capacity minus used
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty predicate: head == tail.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if head equals tail; otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_is_empty" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 16
    If head is equal to tail:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Full predicate: (tail + 1) mod alloc_size == head.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Compute next_tail = (tail + 1) mod alloc_size.
2) Return 1 if next_tail equals head.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_is_full" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 16
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let next_tail be tail plus 1
    If next_tail is greater than or equal to alloc_size:
        Set next_tail to next_tail minus alloc_size
    End If
    If next_tail is equal to head:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WRITE PATH
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Write up to count bytes from the source buffer into the ring buffer.
Writes the minimum of count and available_write bytes, splitting into
at most two contiguous spans if the write wraps the end of the
internal storage. Returns the number of bytes actually written.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty / null checks.
2) writable = min(count, available_write).
3) If writable == 0 return 0.
4) first_span = min(writable, alloc_size - tail).
5) memory_copy data + tail <- src, first_span.
6) Advance tail by first_span; if it reaches alloc_size, wrap to 0.
7) If writable > first_span, copy remaining from src + first_span.
8) Update tail in header.
9) Return writable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(count). Two memory_copy calls in the wrap-around case.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked against available_write; never writes past capacity.
Returns 0 for null inputs or count <= 0.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_write" takes rb as Integer, src as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If src is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let available be proc rb_available_write with rb
    Let writable be count
    If writable is greater than available:
        Set writable to available
    End If
    If writable is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 16
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let first_span be alloc_size minus tail
    If first_span is greater than writable:
        Set first_span to writable
    End If
    Let dst_first be data plus tail
    proc memory_copy from Memory with dst_first, src, first_span
    Let remaining be writable minus first_span
    If remaining is greater than 0:
        Let src_second be src plus first_span
        proc memory_copy from Memory with data, src_second, remaining
    End If
    Let new_tail be tail plus writable
    If new_tail is greater than or equal to alloc_size:
        Set new_tail to new_tail minus alloc_size
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 16, new_tail
    Return writable
End Process

@Reasoning
Append a single byte to the buffer. Returns 1 if successful, 0 if the
buffer is full.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Full check.
2) Store byte at data[tail].
3) Advance tail (with wrap).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 if the buffer is full or rb is null.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_write_byte" takes rb as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let full be proc rb_is_full with rb
    If full is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 16
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let byte_val be value bitwise and 255
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with data, tail, byte_val
    Let new_tail be tail plus 1
    If new_tail is greater than or equal to alloc_size:
        Set new_tail to new_tail minus alloc_size
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 16, new_tail
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: READ PATH
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Read up to max_count bytes into the destination buffer. Returns the
number of bytes actually read.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Null checks.
2) readable = min(max_count, available_read).
3) first_span = min(readable, alloc_size - head).
4) memory_copy dst <- data + head, first_span.
5) Advance head by first_span (wrap if needed).
6) If readable > first_span, copy remaining into dst + first_span.
7) Update head in header.
8) Return readable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(max_count). Two memory_copy calls in wrap-around case.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checked against available_read. Returns 0 for null inputs or
max_count <= 0.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_read" takes rb as Integer, dst as Integer, max_count as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If max_count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let available be proc rb_available_read with rb
    Let readable be max_count
    If readable is greater than available:
        Set readable to available
    End If
    If readable is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let first_span be alloc_size minus head
    If first_span is greater than readable:
        Set first_span to readable
    End If
    Let src_first be data plus head
    proc memory_copy from Memory with dst, src_first, first_span
    Let remaining be readable minus first_span
    If remaining is greater than 0:
        Let dst_second be dst plus first_span
        proc memory_copy from Memory with dst_second, data, remaining
    End If
    Let new_head be head plus readable
    If new_head is greater than or equal to alloc_size:
        Set new_head to new_head minus alloc_size
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 8, new_head
    Return readable
End Process

@Reasoning
Remove and return a single byte from the buffer. Returns -1 if the
buffer is empty so callers can distinguish a real zero byte from
end-of-stream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check (return -1).
2) Load data[head].
3) Advance head with wrap.
4) Return byte (0..255 as Integer).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on empty.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_read_byte" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let empty be proc rb_is_empty with rb
    If empty is equal to 1:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    Let byte_val be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with data, head
    Let new_head be head plus 1
    If new_head is greater than or equal to alloc_size:
        Set new_head to new_head minus alloc_size
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 8, new_head
    Return byte_val
End Process

@Reasoning
Peek a single byte from the buffer without advancing the read cursor.
Returns -1 if the buffer is empty.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check (return -1).
2) Load data[head] and return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns -1 on empty.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_peek_byte" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let empty be proc rb_is_empty with rb
    If empty is equal to 1:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 8
    Return proc memory_get_byte from Memory with data, head
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RESET
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Reset the buffer to the empty state without freeing storage.
Both head and tail are zeroed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read current alloc_size.
2) Set head = 0, tail = 0.
3) Zero the storage so stale bytes never leak into future reads
   (defense in depth - the cursor invariants alone are enough).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(alloc_size) due to the zero fill.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defense-in-depth zero of storage; safe to call on a non-null buffer.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "rb_reset" takes rb as Integer returns Integer:
    If rb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let data be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 0
    Let alloc_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rb, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rb, 16, 0
    If data is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_fill from Memory with data, 0, alloc_size
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
